Fix C — Batch Supabase upsert (eliminate N+1 calls)
Right now syncing 3 resumes fires 6 separate Supabase round-trips. Supabase supports batch upsert in one call.
Prompt for DeepSeek:
In src/context/ResumeSyncContext.tsx, find the syncToCloud() function. It currently loops over profiles with a for...of loop, firing a SELECT + UPDATE/INSERT per profile — that's N×2 round-trips.

Replace the entire loop with a single batch upsert:

async function syncToCloud(profiles: ResumeProfile[], userId: string) {
  if (!isSupabaseConfigured || !supabase) return

  const rows = profiles.map(p => ({
    id: p.id,
    user_id: userId,
    title: p.title,
    resume_data: p,
    updated_at: new Date().toISOString(),
  }))

  const { error } = await supabase
    .from('resumes')
    .upsert(rows, { onConflict: 'id', ignoreDuplicates: false })

  if (error) {
    console.error('Batch sync failed:', error)
    throw error
  }
}

Make sure the function signature and all callers remain the same. The return type stays void. Keep the existing error handling around the call site — only replace the internal loop body.

Note: this requires the Supabase resumes table to have a unique constraint on id. Verify this in supabase-schema.sql — if id is the primary key (which it should be), upsert on conflict: 'id' works correctly.

Fix D — Unify BentoDashboard with completionHelper
Two places compute section completion with different thresholds. When you change one, the other silently diverges.
Prompt for DeepSeek:
In src/components/BentoDashboard.tsx, the allSectionStats useMemo block computes its own completion percentages and statuses from scratch (contactPoints logic, summaryPercent, skillLen >= 5 for complete, etc.).

Replace the entire allSectionStats useMemo with one that derives from getSectionStatus() from completionHelper:

import { getSectionStatus } from '../utils/completionHelper'

const allSectionStats = useMemo(() => {
  const boolStatus = getSectionStatus(resumeData)
  
  // Map boolean complete/incomplete to the percent+status shape BentoDashboard needs
  // For sections where we want a partial state, compute it here from resumeData directly
  // but only for display — completeness truth comes from getSectionStatus

  const result: Record<SectionType, { percent: number; status: 'empty' | 'partial' | 'complete'; label: string }> = {} as Record<SectionType, ...>

  const SECTION_LABELS: Record<SectionType, string> = {
    contact: 'Contact Info', summary: 'Profile Summary', experience: 'Work Experience',
    education: 'Education', skills: 'Core Skills', languages: 'Languages',
    projects: 'Projects', awards: 'Awards & Honors', certifications: 'Certifications',
    interests: 'Interests', publications: 'Publications', references: 'References',
    volunteer: 'Volunteer',
  }

  for (const key of Object.keys(boolStatus) as SectionType[]) {
    const isComplete = boolStatus[key]
    // For sections with array data, check if array is empty for 'empty' state
    const isEmpty = (() => {
      if (key === 'contact') return !resumeData.contact?.fullName?.trim() && !resumeData.contact?.email?.trim()
      if (key === 'summary') return !resumeData.summary?.trim()
      const arr = (resumeData as Record<string, unknown>)[key]
      return Array.isArray(arr) ? arr.length === 0 : false
    })()
    
    result[key] = {
      percent: isComplete ? 100 : isEmpty ? 0 : 50,
      status: isComplete ? 'complete' : isEmpty ? 'empty' : 'partial',
      label: SECTION_LABELS[key],
    }
  }
  return result
}, [resumeData])

This removes the divergence — there's now exactly one source of truth for what "complete" means.

